<subSubSection id="9ECC98D7C75AFF9043FDB90B61D3FA05" pageId="11" pageNumber="412" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="D669CB5CC75AFF9043FDB90B61D3FA05" blockId="11.[151,1437,151,1437]" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">
<emphasis id="E4A2174EC75AFF9043FDB90B645DFACD" bold="true" box="[199,315,1339,1365]" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="11D6B0DFC75AFF904279B90B67FAFACC" box="[323,668,1339,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Atheta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="412" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="yamamotoi" subGenus="Dimetrota">
<emphasis id="E4A2174EC75AFF904279B90B64EAFACD" box="[323,396,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">Atheta</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="E4A2174EC75AFF9042A7B90B6769FACC" box="[413,527,1339,1364]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">Dimetrota</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="E4A2174EC75AFF90411AB90B67FAFACC" box="[544,668,1339,1364]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">yamamotoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very similar to 
<taxonomicName id="11D6B0DFC75AFF904050B90B613EFACD" baseAuthorityName="Sharp" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[874,1112,1339,1365]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Atheta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="412" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="transfuga" subGenus="Atheta">
<emphasis id="E4A2174EC75AFF904050B90B661DFACD" box="[874,891,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">A</emphasis>
. (
<emphasis id="E4A2174EC75AFF9040A9B90B66BAFACD" box="[915,988,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">Atheta</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="E4A2174EC75AFF9040D7B90B613EFACD" box="[1005,1112,1339,1365]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">transfuga</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but can be distinguished by the male sternite VIII (
<figureCitation id="4EEDD7D9C75AFF9042ABB96F6480FAE1" box="[401,486,1375,1401]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1789,1813]" captionTargetBox="[167,1432,191,1750]" captionTargetId="figure-29@12.[151,1436,181,1765]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 7. Atheta (Dimetrota) yamamotoi. A: antenna; B: male abdominal tergite VIII (dorsal aspect); C: male abdominal sternite VIII (ventral aspect); D: female abdominal tergite VIII (dorsal aspect); E: female abdominal sternite VIII (ventral aspect); F: median lobe of aedeagus (lateral aspect); G: median lobe of aedeagus (ventral aspect); H: paramere (lateral aspect); I: spermatheca. Scales = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6571564" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6571564/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">Fig. 7C</figureCitation>
) with about 10 macrosetae on each side of midline; female sternite VIII (
<figureCitation id="4EEDD7D9C75AFF904633B96F603BFAE1" box="[1289,1373,1375,1401]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="12.[151,250,1789,1813]" captionTargetBox="[167,1432,191,1750]" captionTargetId="figure-29@12.[151,1436,181,1765]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURE 7. Atheta (Dimetrota) yamamotoi. A: antenna; B: male abdominal tergite VIII (dorsal aspect); C: male abdominal sternite VIII (ventral aspect); D: female abdominal tergite VIII (dorsal aspect); E: female abdominal sternite VIII (ventral aspect); F: median lobe of aedeagus (lateral aspect); G: median lobe of aedeagus (ventral aspect); H: paramere (lateral aspect); I: spermatheca. Scales = 0.1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6571564" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6571564/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">Fig. 7E</figureCitation>
) with 7 macrosetae on each side of midline. This species is recorded here for the first time in 
<collectingCountry id="AEC18BCCC75AFF904753B9B361D7FA05" box="[1129,1201,1411,1437]" name="South Korea" pageId="11" pageNumber="412">Korea</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
